Mission:
BRAIN-002

Title:
Memory Engine

Goal:
Give Atlas real, persistent memory of its own decisions and workflow history so it stops starting every session from a blank slate.

Focus:
Already implemented at src/atlas/brain/memory/ — MemoryEngine.ts, MemoryStore.ts, MemoryRegistry.ts, MemoryContext.ts, MemorySearch.ts, workflowMemory.ts, bootstrap.ts, memory.types.ts, index.ts (real code — read these before proposing anything new here)
Persistence already exists, but as a manual wrapper OUTSIDE the module: scripts/atlas-runtime.ts (loadMemoryFromDisk/persistMemoryToDisk functions, writes to reports/memory/store.json) imports/exports the in-memory store on every cycle — read this file before proposing a new persistence path, so you either integrate with reports/memory/store.json or explicitly replace/simplify the wrapper in atlas-runtime.ts, never add a second, parallel memory file
Decision Engine recall of its own recent verdicts before deciding (already wired — see src/atlas/brain/decision/AutonomousDecision.ts recallRecentDecisions())
Workflow memory integration (saveWorkflowMemory) — check src/atlas/brain/memory/workflowMemory.ts before assuming this is missing
Semantic/vector recall (still genuinely missing — current search in MemorySearch.ts is keyword-only) — this is the one legitimate net-new increment, not persistence

Constraints:
Provider-independent Brain module
Memory failures must never block a decision (best-effort read/write)
No fictional or mock memory entries — only entries generated by real Atlas activity

Success:
The always-on runtime (atlas-runtime.ts) restarts and its memory entry count keeps growing instead of resetting to zero, and the Decision Engine's reasoning references its own prior verdicts from persisted memory.
